%N A368052 The degree of polynomials related to Somos-4 sequences. Also for n > 2 the degree of the (n-3)-th involution in a family of involutions in the Cremona group of rank 3 defined by a Somos-4 sequence.
%C A368052 Let s(0), s(1), s(2), s(3) be the 4 initial values in a Somos-4 sequence. The following terms s(4), s(5), ... are rational expressions in the 4 initial values derived from the Somos-4 recurrence: s(n) = ( s(n-1)*s(n-3) + s(n-2)^2 ) / s(n-4). E.g., s(4) = (s(1)*s(3) + s(2)^2) / s(0), s(5) = (s(0)*s(3)^2 + s(1)*s(2)*s(3) + s(2)^3) / (s(0)*s(1)), s(6) = ... .
%C A368052 Because of the Laurent property of a Somos-4 sequence the denominator of these terms is a monomial in the initial values.
%C A368052 Define the polynomial G(n) to be the numerator of s(n), so ..., G(2) = s(2), G(3) = s(3), G(4) = s(1)*s(3) + s(2)^2, G(5) = s(0)*s(3)^2 + s(1)*s(2)*s(3) + s(2)^3, ...
%C A368052 For n >= 0, a term a(n) of the actual sequence is the degree of G(n). The degree of the denominator of s(n) is a(n) - 1.
%C A368052 This Somos-4 sequence defines a family (proposed Somos family) S of (birational) involutions in Cr_3(R), the Cremona group of rank 3.
%C A368052 A Somos involution S(n) in this family is defined as S(n) : RP^3 -> RP^3, (s(0) : s(1) : s(2) : s(3)) -> (s(n+3) : s(n+2) : s(n+1) : s(n)) = (G(n+3) : G(n+2)*m1 : G(n+1)*m2 : G(n)*m3 ), with m1, m2, m3 monomials. The involutions generate an infinite dihedral group. Already 2 consecutive involutions S(n), S(n+1) generate this group too. This group as a dihedral group has 2 conjugacy classes { ..., S(0), S(2), S(4), ... } and { ..., S(1), S(3), S(5), ... } of involutions. The degree of such an involution S(n) equals the degree of G(n+3) and the term a(n+3) in the actual sequence.
%H A368052 S. Fomin and A. Zelevinsky, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0104241">The Laurent phenomemon</a>, arXiv:math/0104241 [math.CO], 2001.
%H A368052 <a href="/index/Rec#order_07">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (3,-3,1,-1,3,-3,1).
%F A368052 For n > 3, a(n) = 1 + b(n-2) + b(n-1) + b(n) + b(n+1), where b(n) = A220838(n) is the exponent of one of the initial values in the denominator of s(n). - _Andrey Zabolotskiy_, Dec 22 2023
%F A368052 G.f.: 1 + x + x^2 + x^3 + x^4*(2 - 3*x + 2*x^2)/((1 - x)^3*(1 + x^4)). - _Michael Somos_, Dec 27 2023
%e A368052 Step 1: calculate s(4) = (s(1)*s(3) + s(2)^2) / s(0). Step 2: apply the recurrence, now for s(5) we get s(5) = (s(2)*s(4) + s(3)^2) / s(1). Substituting s(4) in this expression for the s(4) calculated in step 1 results in s(5) = (s(0)*s(3)^2 + s(1)*s(2)*s(3) + s(2)^3) / (s(0)*s(1)), s(6) = ... .
%e A368052 Then the polynomials G() are G(0) = s(0), G(1) = s(1), G(2) = s(2), G(3) = s(3), G(4) = s(1)*s(3) + s(2)^2, G(5) = s(0)*s(3)^2 + s(1)*s(2)*s(3) + s(2)^3, ... and the sequence terms are the degrees of G(); they are a(0) ... a(3) = 1, a(4) = 2, a(5) = 3 ... starting with offset 0.
%e A368052 The Somos involution S(0) is the map ( s(0) : s(1) : s(2) : s(3) ) -> (G(3) : G(2)*m1 : G(1)*m2 : G(0)*m3 ) = (s(3) : s(2) : s(1) : s(0) ) with the monomials m1, m2, m3 = 1; it is a permutation, a linear map with degree 1.
%e A368052 The Somos involution S(1) is the map ( s(0) : s(1) : s(2) : s(3) ) -> (G(4) : G(3)*m1 : G(2)*m2 : G(1)*m3 ) = (s(1)*s(3) + s(2)^2 : s(3)*s(0) : s(2)*s(0) : s(1)*s(0)) now with other monomials m1, m2, m3 = s(0). The degree of the map is the degree of G(4) equals 2.
%t A368052 s[n_?(#>3 &)] := s[n] = Together[(s[n-1] s[n-3] + s[n-2]^2) / s[n-4]];
%t A368052 Table[Exponent[Numerator[s[n]] /. {s[_] :> s}, s], {n, 0, 17}] (* or *)
%t A368052 LinearRecurrence[{3, -3, 1, -1, 3, -3, 1}, {1, 1, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 10, 14, 18}, 40] (* _Andrey Zabolotskiy_, Dec 22 2023 *)
%t A368052 a[ n_] := Which[ n>3, SeriesCoefficient[ x^4*(2 - 3*x + 2*x^2)/((1 - x)^3*(1 + x^4)), {x, 0, n}], n<0, a[3-n], True, 1]; (* _Michael Somos_, Dec 27 2023 *)
%o A368052 (Maxima) /* Somos-4, the polynomials G () and the degree of G () */
%o A368052 Len : 12$
%o A368052 S : makelist (0, Len)$
%o A368052 G : makelist (0, Len - 4)$
%o A368052 DegG : makelist (0, Len - 4)$   /* G, the numerator of s() */
%o A368052 H : makelist (0, Len - 4)$   /* H, the denominator of s() */
%o A368052 for i: 1 thru 4 do ( S[i] : s[i - 1] )$
%o A368052 for i: 5 thru Len do (
%o A368052     /* the Somos-4 recursion */
%o A368052     S[i] : factor ((S[i - 1] * S[i - 3] + S[i - 2] ** 2) / S[i - 4]),
%o A368052     G[i - 4] : num (S[i - 1]), H[i - 4] : denom (S[i - 1]),
%o A368052     /* I do not know a simple way in Maxima to calculate the degree in s[0], s[1], s[2], s[3] of the polynomial G, so I use: the degree of the polynomial G is 1 + the degree of H, and H is a monomial in s[0], s[1], s[2], s[3] */
%o A368052     DegG[i - 4] : 1 + hipow (H[i - 4], s[0]) + hipow (H[i - 4], s[1]) + hipow (H[i - 4], s[2]) + hipow (H[i - 4], s[3])
%o A368052 )$
%o A368052 /* to show that the monomial H(n - 1) divides H(n) */
%o A368052 RatH : makelist (0, Len - 4)$   /* the ratio H(n + 1) / H(n), this should be a polynomial, i.e., the denominator of the ratio has to be 1 */
%o A368052 for i : 2 thru Len - 4 do ( RatH[i] : H[i] / H[i - 1]);
%o A368052 display (/* S, */ G, DegG, H, RatH);
